Of the many advances in agriculture technology in recent years, many say the biggest benefit is the ability for farmers to share data that can lead to higher crop yields.\
\
But for the millions of farmers in the developing world, data-sharing and analysis isn't possible when most of the industry doesn't have access to the internet.\
\
So Wefarm Ltd., a London-based startup operating in a few African countries, created a digital network that connects small-scale farmers with agricultural information via old-style SMS.\
\
The company, which was founded in 2015, just raised a $5 million seed round led by True Ventures, with participation from LocalGlobe and Accelerated Digital Ventures. Individual investors including Skype founder Niklas Zennstrom and Blue Bottle Coffee Chief Executive Bryan Meehan also contributed.\
\
Wefarm is used by some 640,000 farmers in Kenya and Uganda, who can ask a question via SMS in their own language about anything agriculture-related, according to the company. Wefarm says it then applies 
\f2\b machine learning
\f1\b0  to distill the most relevant answers from the network users.\
\
Conducting business via basic mobile phones is common in Africa, where millions of people use mobile banking service M-Pesa to transfer money or even take out insurance policies. Wefarm Chief Executive Kenny Ewan said the familiarity with mobile phones quickly made the company popular with farmers, and the platform has a 90% user-retention rate.\
\
He said the funding will be used to develop new features such as a digital farming assistant. Wefarm also intends to create a marketplace for buying and selling crops\'97imilar to what the Farmer's Business Network Inc. offers in the U.S. and Canada.\
\
"Wefarm not only democratizes technology in a big but overlooked market, but it allows for a level of supply chain transparency you couldn't get anywhere else," said True Ventures co-founder Jon Callaghan.\
