BEIJING\'97hinese authorities are cutting the amount of cash banks are required to set aside to cover bad loans, a move that would boost lenders' bottom line but potentially increase financial risk.\
\
With the sector struggling to boost profits, the country's banking regulator will lower the provision coverage ratio for commercial banks\'97 requirement to safeguard their ability to weather losses\'97o a range of 120%-150%, from the current minimum of 150% of their bad loans, according to people familiar with the situation.\
\
One of the people said the China Banking Regulatory Commission handed a document announcing the relaxation to its local bureaus last week, rendering the move effective immediately.\
\
Lowering the required threshold is "conducive to speeding up the disposal of current nonperforming loans," Wang Zhaoxing, a vice chairman at the regulatory commission, told state media on Tuesday.\
\
Beijing is trying to release more credit into the economy to keep growth humming, even as it tries to tighten financing to overheated areas like property. Analysts say the move is an acknowledgment by authorities that growth isn't booming like before. "They're trying to release capital otherwise stuck in the financial system," says Jonas Short, an analyst at Everbright Sun Hung Kai Co. Ltd.\
\
At the same time, the relaxation comes as financial regulators have been trying to get banks to rein in risky lending and investment practices. It is indicative, say analysts, of the huge sway lenders retain over their watchdog.\
\
Chinese banks began lowering the amount of cash they are required to set aside as early as the first quarter of 2016, when a tide of souring corporate loans brought profit levels near zero across the industry. They appeared not to face regulatory consequences.\
\
Industrial & Commercial Bank of China Ltd., the world's largest lender by assets, said at the time it set its buffer ratio at 141%. The bank has continued to keep its ratio below the regulatory threshold, reporting 148% as of the end of September.\
\
Bank of China Ltd. was another big state lender to lower its impairment provision in 2016. The lender told The Wall Street Journal at the time that a declining ratio had become a trend in China, and that it was cutting the ratio to accommodate an acceleration of loan write-offs.\
\
Analysts are skeptical as to whether lowering the capital requirement would prompt banks to fully disclose the extent of their bad debt. Bad loans accounted for 1.74% of banks' total loans at the end of 2017, according to official data, a level far lower than what most analysts believe to be true.\
\
Lenders have lobbied since 2015 for regulators to lower cash buffer requirements so they could free up more cash and spur profits. The CBRC's Mr. Wang said the industry's provision coverage ratio currently averaged 180%.\
\
A vice president at one global rating firm said the relaxation was "credit negative" for the sector. He declined to be named, citing worries his employer wouldn't agree. "They may have been forced to," he said of regulators' decision. "Concerns about weakened risk management have to be balanced against banks' desire for strong profitability."\
