Take France. In 2012, the French president at the time, Fran\'e7is Hollande, called finance the "enemy" and imposed a wealth tax. But soon after the U.K. voted for Brexit, Mr. Hollande's government extended rules that allow employees recruited abroad to claim 30% of their salary as an "impatriate premium," which is income-tax free for up to eight years. There are further tax rebates including those for days worked outside France. In total, expats based in France can get up to half of their salary exempted from income tax.\
